{"cursor":"15015","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Precipitation' is widely used in downstream processing of biological products,\nsuch as proteins. [http://www.rcsb.org/pdb/home/home.do] This unit operation\nserves to concentrate and fractionate the target product from various\ncontaminants. For example, in the biotechnology industry protein precipitation\nis used to eliminate contaminants commonly contained in blood. [http://www.pharmaceutical-int.com/categories/protein-precipitation/protein-\nprecipitation-plates-tubes.asp] Academic research on protein precipitation\nexplores new protein precipitation methods.\n[http://www.cchem.berkeley.edu/hwbgrp/research_files/protein_crystal.html] The\nunderlying mechanism of precipitation is to alter the solvation potential of the\nsolvent and thus lower the solubility of the solute by addition of a reagent.\n","linknr":177,"url":"Protein_precipitation","recorded":1362672854,"links":15,"instances":["journal","fluid","biochemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Biotechnology"],"headings":["Protein solubility","Repulsive electrostatic force","Attractive electrostatic force","Precipitate formation","Salting out","Isoelectric point precipitation","Precipitation with organic solvents","Non-ionic hydrophilic polymers","Flocculation by polyelectrolytes","Polyvalent metallic ions","Precipitation reactors","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/IonicSolvationLayerNew.jpg/120px-IonicSolvationLayerNew.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/HydrationLayerNew.jpg/120px-HydrationLayerNew.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/HydrationLayer2New.jpg/120px-HydrationLayer2New.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/e/e/aee745ece09879a32af81b55fea153a0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/f/2/7f21babd02b791114390a16e3fe7b02a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/a/f/aafc9406ac63267f41acaac5e8f4bbaf.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/2/1/321655841e6eb1dfb52ac657